Find the least positive four-digit solution to the following system of congruences. \begin{align*}
7x &\equiv 21 \pmod{14} \\
2x+13 &\equiv 16 \pmod{9} \\
-2x+1 &\equiv x \pmod{25} \\
\end{align*}

inference:
For the first equation: \begin{align*}
7x &\equiv 21 \pmod{14} \\
\Rightarrow\qquad x &\equiv 1 \pmod{2} \\
\Rightarrow\qquad x &=1, 3, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13.
\end{align*}

For the second equation: \begin{align*}
2x+13 &\equiv 16 \pmod{9} \\
\Rightarrow\qquad 2x &\equiv 3 \pmod{9} \\
\Rightarrow\qquad x &\equiv 8 \pmod{3} \\
\Rightarrow\qquad x &=8, 11, 14, \dots.
\end{align*}

For the third equation: \begin{align*}
-2x+1 &\equiv x \pmod{25} \\
\Rightarrow\qquad -3x &\equiv -1 \pmod{25} \\
\Rightarrow\qquad 3x &\equiv 1 \pmod{25} \\
\Rightarrow\qquad x &\equiv 15 \pmod{5} \\
\Rightarrow\qquad x &=15, 20, 25, \dots.
\end{align*}

Combining the three solutions, we get \begin{align*}
x &=1, 3, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13, 15, 20, 25, \dots.
\end{align*}

The least positive four-digit solution is $\boxed{1003}$.
Final Answer: $\boxed{1003}$. I hope it is correct.

